column1: Before 1 January 2023, will Amazon or a subsidiary use a Zoox autonomous vehicle to deliver a package and/or for a public ride-hailing service?
column5: ['Yes, only to deliver a package but not for a public ride-hailing service', 'Yes, only a for public ride-hailing service but not to deliver a package', 'Yes, both to deliver a package and for a public ride-hailing service', 'No']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology']
"Before 1 Jan 2023" is a long way from the closing date of July 1, 2021
Elon sent a tesla to space. Will Bezos deliver to the Moon?
There is a need for regulations that will not be ready for ride-hailing. Package might be ok, only in certain tech-savy areas
2023 is too optimistic for the timeline. I legitimately cannot imagine this being done until 2024 at the earliest.
Now owned by Amazon, Zoox progressive cullture and hiring practices have become a PR vehicle for the parent.
I used to be a big fan. But the bottom line up front is thath Zoox has a great "culture" for media mavens to bandy about, but look who the bigs are choosing... everybody but Amazon owned Zoox...

Current technologies can already perform similar functions. I assume that the technology for package delivery and ride-hailing would be similar, with variation being based on cargo. Issue of safety is the variable that requires testing and verification in the field to eliminate or reduce liability. Most likely packaging delivery will be rolled out first and assessed and once satisfied, public ride-hailing will quickly follow.

With a deadline to the question at 1-3/4 years from now, it sure seems that Amazon would have the capacity to put together an autonomous vehicle on the road for some limited commercial usage. A few cities are already allowing autonomous vehicles and 29 states "allow" them. It seems package delivery is a bit harder....similar to the last mile problem...how to get the last 100 yrds (from vehicle to doorstep, record the delivery, etc. Would this be a robot? Does the vehicle have to wait around for the customer to meet the vehicle and unload it?)
I think it is more likely that amazon will use it for taxi services rather than package delivery.
It'll deliver non breakable products first

The question is very broad. Food is already being delivered autonomously in my hometown today by a start up. If Amazon doesn’t a prof of concept on delivery under already it will in weeks or maybe months, certainly not years. Same for ride hail, especially given question specifically allowing for no charge. Will change answer if becomes clear Amazon has no interest in ride hailing and only in delivery.

Big change in my forecast Thanks @Jayce for your comment https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1261119 Initially had assumed Zoox would go the Nuro way (their R2 vehicle looks pretty similar to Zoox) and Nuro has actually started deliveries for dominos.https://www.therobotreport.com/nuro-r2-autonomously-delivering-dominos-pizza-houston/ And Zoox now being owned by Amazon, it was a fairly simple assumption to make that they would go down a similar road(ie deliveries before robotaxi). But it seems they are more interested in the ride hailing market initially before pursuing the automatic delivery opportunity. Following is an excerpt from the interview with the current CTO, and cofounder When we first started talking to Amazon, we had the same thought you did: This is a company that moves a lot of stuff around, and that they'd probably be interested in moving around autonomously. It's a good idea! And it's not that they're not interested in that. They are interested in that. But to their immense credit, when we started talking to them last year, they actually got even more excited about what we're already doing, which is an entirely new market for them. https://www.protocol.com/zoox-self-driving-car
Revised to add a lot more weight to bucket 2 and go up a bit on no thanks to this comment and article provided by @Jayce. https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1261119

Pese a que zoox ya tiene pruebas autorizadas tanto en Las Vegas como en California, teniendo el permiso de transportar personas en su auto con nivel 5 en conducción autonoma (que la persona no puede tomar control del auto) en esas zonas, creo que el tema ético en lo que son accidentes y muertes debido a un auto sin conductor, es un tema todavía poco debatido. Es por esto que creo que va a tener muchas barreras políticas para su lanzamiento de transporte urbano y/o entrega de paquetes. Además creo que el no prevalece por las otras alternativas, ya que su CEO Aicha Evans, estableció en una entrevista que no lo tendrían listo para el próximo año, pero si antes de lo que todos esperan. Agregó en la misma entrevista que primero iban a transportar personas y posteriormente adaptar el sistema para paquetes, por lo que mi segunda opción fue esa. Finalmente le di un 20% a que entreguen paquetes antes del 2023 y no personas, por la experiencia que le puede entregar amazon en la tecnología utilizada en sus bodegas, y por el interés asociado que tiene para que surja en este ámbito lo antes posible

As reported city Council looks to expand remote controlled delivery a possible amendment to municipality code code soon allow remote control delivery services in the zero emission delivery zone program to serve businesses in all. The company CyanRobotics deployed autonomous electrified delivery vehicle on city sidewalks and pedestrian pathways of travel as it sought to offer contactless delivery options that would help residents receive everything from sunscreen to ice cream. “ How will the question resolve?
Two years is a long time in this space, anything can happen, and most likely will.
Time update
This will be a very limited and restricted exercise. There won’t be any delivery down fifth Avenue in New York City

Amazon is a very innovative company and quick to embrace new technology. It is also laser focused on cutting costs. Thus, as soon as Zoox vehicles are available, Amazon is very likely to adopt them for package delivery. It may also use it for ride-hailing provided Amazon enters into this business. Since it is not in this business currently, it is unlikely to enter this business in the next 18 months.
@whitecake's comment + source [1,2].

CEO says there won't be a commercial service until after next year and that they will do package delivery only after a ride-hailing service. https://www.bloomberg.com/news/videos/2021-03-09/zoox-ceo-on-deal-with-amazon-to-make-self-driving-electric-cars-video
moving closer to consensus
Buying lots of Rivian EV vans for delivery, but seems likely to also attempt to use Zoox in-house vehicles, perhaps as next-gen delivery vehicles or for specific sectors / markets
Updated slightly as I think the crowd is conservative on only package and I feel like I should be ahead of them on that. See previous forecast for more details.

https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/auto-technology/zoox-gets-driverless-car-test-permit-in-california-a-win-for-amazon/78200337 the bar seems very low to resolve this question, as long as some customer lives on the streets they have received a permit for, they just need to put a package into the car at the HQ and successfully deliver it to said customer. Also, for ride-hailing, they just need someone (does it need to be outside Amazon even?) to take a ride on these streets they have received a permit for. I am not sure the permit allows passengers though. Regardless, they will very likely first deliver a package. It is therefore much more likely that they will both deliver a package and perform ride-hailing, than just ride-hailing alone. I updated the forecast to take all this into account.

In all contexts I see these items only occurring in markets that are unusually conducive to autonomous vehicle operation, and probably in a "demo" context. There are conditions today that would allow for package delivery or ridesharing using autonomous vehicles but they aren't scalable yet to a mass market and for Zoox I would imagine them to require a few years additional time to do what some providers (Waymo in pre-mapped cities, Tesla with a low success rate relative to human drivers so far) can do today.

Autonomous driving requires much stronger algorithms (ai) than currently available. Current status of the algorithms is good enough for autonomous driving on highways and good weather conditions, but fail in navigating crowded down streets and bad weather conditions. It is expected that it will take several decades before we have algorithms with these capabilities (see for example rebooting ai, for Gary Marcus)
Last mile delivery is difficult to do quickly and safely.
Amazon just bought the company. There is no more Zoox. So, sorry for the confusion - 2 years with working model... sure what scale? who knows...
Never heard of Zoox; Amazon buying their own stuff; already have humans - with low cost etc.
Waymo is already doing it for ride share. Amazon will try to get in on the space in the next two years with bot deliveries.

Move into public ride-sharing suggests entry into what is an increasingly crowded local market oriented business where Amazon would be late to market. Same would hold for takeout food delivery. This suggests that the self-driving technology is most of interest.

https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-12-14/amazon-s-zoox-unveils-robotaxi-for-future-ride-hailing-service Zoox has passed all crash tests and will be used in limited locations for package delivery --reducing the potential passenger dangers. There will be select locations in the US where ride-hailing will be permitted. But, given the haphazard nature of most areas of the US, the most likely use of Zoox is for last mile delivery from regional Amazon warehouses to Google GPS-mapped locations (ie, fleet management). They may also deploy their in house fleet management infrastructure as an enterprise product (using the same strategic philosophy that launched AWS. Although it's not a forecastable option here, I think municipal or private campus shuttles and buses may be more likely than ride-hailing applications. Especially in Amazon owned locations.
Legislation framework missing and COVID impacts
Incomplete question. It could be a final-block delivery or ride.

I am much more skeptical than the crowd that Zoox will be used to deliver a package. I have doubts it will redesign vehicles for package delivery before completing its driverless taxi given it is specifically focused on ride-hailing and the company's autonomous situation following the acquisition. Additionally, this question is very restrictive since it is only considering vehicles made by Zoox. If the question asked if Amazon would use an autonomous vehicle for package delivery or a public ride-hailing my forecasts would be much higher.

"Delivering a package" is a low bar, but all the chatter is around ride hailing. Even if this is purely a prospective acquisition, ownership of Zoox suggests a desire to be a multi-vertical innovator: like the Apple of services (Apple of course will have plenty to say about this.)

"A public ride-hailing service does not need to involve payment to count for resolution." It seems that it includes beta testers, so I think there's a reasonable chance of that happening in 2021-2022. However, autonomous package delivering is much more likely to happen:

Zoox unveiled a working automous vehicle in Dec 2020: https://www.cnbc.com/2020/12/14/amazons-self-driving-company-zoox-unveils-autonomous-robotaxi.html . It seems likely that both a package delivery and ride-hailing demonstration will happen by Jan 1, 2023. If only one demo happens, it will likely be ride-hailing based on the Dec 2020 information not mentioning package delivery.

Delivering one package could be completed by simply sending a package from one remote location to another. I do not think they will be running widespread autonomous delivery. In the off chance there they can make an autonomous ride hailing service, they would also be delivering packages.

The question is akin to the use of drones for package delivery. Assuming that the events are satisfied if one package has been delivered to a customer or one passenger has hailed a ride, these can be achieved in a quasi experimental setting. Whether either is commercialised is a different question.
Feels pretty likely/east publicity to deliver a package, but does not seem to be that much rush.

Apple targets car production by 2024 and eyes 'next level' battery technology PUBLISHED MON, DEC 21 2020 3:48 PM EST UPDATED MON, DEC 21 2020 4:14 PM EST SHARE KEY POINTS Apple is moving forward with self-driving car technology and is targeting 2024 to produce a passenger vehicle that could include its own breakthrough battery technology, people familiar with the matter told Reuters. The iPhone maker's automotive efforts, known as Project Titan, have proceeded unevenly since 2014 when it first started to design its own vehicle from scratch. At one point, Apple drew back the effort to focus on software and reassessed its goals. Since then, Apple has progressed enough that it now aims to build a vehicle for consumers, two people familiar with the effort said

This has two years to play out, that is a long time in FSD, but not many have made it across the general driving threshold yet. Package delivery has the advantage of being on a limited number of high volume routes, so the job territory is constrained. Amazon can easily constrain use to "easily" navigated routes. General ride hailing is much more difficult, in that destinations can be anywhere.
Seems implausible that Amazon would focus on ride-hailing, when clearly delivery is its most pressing concern (and less regulatory challenge)

Nuro already has plans to operate delivery only vehicles and Waymo is already operating driverless taxis in Phoenix. https://techcrunch.com/2020/04/07/nuro-gets-ok-to-test-its-driverless-delivery-vehicles-on-california-public-roads/ So they are in no ways the first ones here. Plus GM-cruise has become the fifth company to get permits for autonomous driving so expect Amazon to go after both markets taxi service and delivery pretty aggressively. The offset factor here is how much they would have to invest here and the time needed to bring this to market. Have not heard much about aurora (their last investment in the space 2 years ago

Waymo is already doing driverless taxis in a limited area in Phoenix. Zoox has received a permit to test on some public roads with no driver. According to the permit requirements that means they must have an SAE level 4 or 5 vehicle which means they're pretty far along. It seems pretty likely to me that they would want to get a program going like Waymo has and that they're capable of it within the next 2 years. Carrying a package I would guess would be the simplest target because you can have a company employee ride along and do the actual delivering. But I'd guess they would aim for a taxi service for the public or members like Waymo is doing. And if they can carry humans it seems absurd that a company owned by Amazon would not use it to deliver a package at least once for PR.

This is a pretty low bar to clear within more than 2 years from now. And it is global too. I almost feel like my probabilities of it happening are too low and that I was conservative due the very conservative crowd.
Amazon already is plowing new ground with its ok to do delivery's by drone - or as we call it down here - Skeet Shooting w/prizes. after a few missed deliveries ground delivery will supplant drones.

Finally some momentum! Not sure why crowd forecast is so negative (I may have misunderstood?). Zoox previously required a safety driver - now not required. https://techcrunch.com/2020/09/18/zoox-becomes-fourth-company-to-land-driverless-testing-permit-in-california/
In past, I was way over-optimistic on EVs and AVs.
Only tangential to this question (doesnt specifically mention Zoox and focused on smaller delivery robots)... https://www.wired.com/story/amazon-fedex-delivery-robots-your-sidewalk/

According to job ads, they seem to mainly look for Hardware engineers, I guess they still have some tough nuts to crack. Delivering a package could be a great MVP/Marketing gag at this stage. Far less complexity than a public ride-hailing service.

Autonomous vehicle technology is definitely far enough along today to warrant a public "commercial" demonstration (multiple autonomous vehicle companies like Waymo, nVidia, and Cruise have already done this). This leads to a high confidence for both package delivery and public ride-hailing service. It's hard to know what Amazon's plans are for Zoox, however, and so I say its a coin-toss about whether they will lean in as ride-hailing only or package delivery only (I think both are potential options). There is a small risk that Zoox/Amazon keep secret their progress, since both are notoriously private about their R&D until a service is ready to be used commercially.
2 years from now is sufficient time to get both up and running
Autonomous vehicles (even ones with a backup driver) are yet to cross many a hurdle (both technical and regulatory).
I see no reason amazon would take on passengers, but not packages.
I'm inclined to put more in "No." I'll let this stew a bit.
28 months. Surprised by the amount of “no” by my peers. Not first time I would be on wrong side of resolution, however. ;)
A business expansion would probably be welcomed by Amazon. Still, it's main business will take priority.

Drone delivery for Amazon is big. I can see a carrier vehicle being dispatched to a neighborhood with smaller drone vehicles doing door to door for 100% autonomous delivery. If not commercialized, Amazon will do some ride sharing experiences similar to Uber.
